<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content -->
  <h1>ESSUM33490 - Shares to which schemes can apply: Employee pre-emption restrictions 
  </h1>
  <p>Paragraph 21(1) provides that even if shares are subject to restrictions which 
    do not attach to all shares of the same class, they may still be acceptable 
    as "scheme shares" if the restrictions are "authorised restrictions" within 
    the meaning of paragraphs 21(2) and (3). <br>
    <br>
    Restrictions authorised by paragraphs 21(2) and (3) are those that require 
    employees and directors to sell their shares when they cease to be employees 
    or directors of the company concerned, or of any company under its control. 
    These are commonly known as "employee pre-emption" restrictions, although 
    that expression does not appear in the legislation. </p>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">Paragraph 21(2) is concerned with whose
shares must be subject to employee pre- emption provisions</li>
<li class="filledcircle">Paragraph 21(3) is concerned with the

terms on which they may be required to sell their shares</li>
</ul>
  <p>To be an "authorised restriction" which does not attach to all shares of the 
    same class, the employee pre-emption provisions must be imposed by the Articles 
    of Association. It is not sufficient for them to be imposed by, for example, 
    the scheme rules or a shareholders agreement. <br>
    <br>
    The concept of employee pre-emption provisions as "authorised restrictions" 
    was introduced by Section 22 FA 1986 with a view to making it easier for smaller 
    companies, which might be concerned to retain some control over who could 
    hold their shares, to use such shares as scheme shares in an approved scheme. 
    "Employee pre-emption" restrictions on shares are commonly, but not exclusively, 
    found in the Articles of Association of private companies. It is unusual to 
    find them in large public companies or in foreign companies. Stock Exchange 
    Regulations do not permit such restrictions on the transfer of shares to be 
    included in the Articles of Association of listed companies. <br>
    <br>
    Employee pre-emption restrictions are only "authorised restrictions" if they 
    meet in full the conditions in Paragraphs 21(2) and (3). Detailed examination 
    of the Articles of Association is therefore required to identify </p>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">whether the shares to be used as scheme

shares are subject to employee pre-emption restrictions and, if

so,</li>
<li class="filledcircle">whether the conditions of paragraphs 21(2)

and (3) are satisfied.</li>
</ul>
  <p>Normally the restrictions which need to be examined in detail are found in 
    the clauses of the Articles of Association headed "Transfer of Shares" or 
    "Transmission of Shares". <br>
    <br>
    The only permitted difference between employee-held shares and other shares 
    of the same class is that the employee-held shares are subject to a compulsory 
    sale when the employment ceases. <br>
    <br>
    Although the employee is compelled to sell, the sale must take place on exactly 
    the same terms as would apply to a sale freely entered into by any other shareholder. 
    The intention is that the self-regulating effect of the general pre-emption 
    procedures (which regulate the transfer of shares generally) should result 
    in fairness in the transfer prices that a ceasing employee or director will 
    receive in the event of a compulsory sale. </p>
